{"format": "tiptap/v1", "updatedAt": "2026-06-22T06:45:39.574Z", "doc": {"type": "doc", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "A "}, {"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "Computation Graph"}, {"type": "text", "text": " (also called computational graph) is a visual and mathematical representation of the flow of data and operations in a neural network, where "}, {"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "nodes represent variables or operations"}, {"type": "text", "text": " and "}, {"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "edges represent the flow of data"}, {"type": "text", "text": " between them. It provides a powerful abstraction for understanding, implementing, and optimizing both forward propagation and backpropagation."}]}, {"type": "horizontalRule"}, {"type": "image", "attrs": {"src": "data:image/svg+xml;base64,", "alt": "Computation Graph — concept overview"}}, {"type": "heading", "attrs": {"level": 2}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "What is a Computation Graph?"}]}, {"type": "heading", "attrs": {"level": 3}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Definition:"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "A computation graph is a "}, {"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "data flow diagram"}, {"type": "text", "text": " that represents all mathematical operations in a neural network:"}]}, {"type": "table", "content": [{"type": "tableRow", "content": [{"type": "tableHeader", "attrs": {"colspan": 1, "rowspan": 1, "colwidth": null, "align": null}, "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Component"}]}]}, {"type": "tableHeader", "attrs": {"colspan": 1, "rowspan": 1, "colwidth": null, "align": null}, "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Meaning"}]}]}]}, {"type": "tableRow", "content": [{"type": "tableCell", "attrs": {"colspan": 1, "rowspan": 1, "colwidth": null, "align": null}, "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "Nodes"}]}]}, {"type": "tableCell", "attrs": {"colspan": 1, "rowspan": 1, "colwidth": null, "align": null}, "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Variables (inputs, weights, biases, activations) or operations (addition, multiplication, activation functions)"}]}]}]}, {"type": "tableRow", "content": [{"type": "tableCell", "attrs": {"colspan": 1, "rowspan": 1, "colwidth": null, "align": null}, "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "Edges"}]}]}, {"type": "tableCell", "attrs": {"colspan": 1, "rowspan": 1, "colwidth": null, "align": null}, "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Directional flow of data (tensors) between nodes"}]}]}]}, {"type": "tableRow", "content": [{"type": "tableCell", "attrs": {"colspan": 1, "rowspan": 1, "colwidth": null, "align": null}, "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "Input nodes"}]}]}, {"type": "tableCell", "attrs": {"colspan": 1, "rowspan": 1, "colwidth": null, "align": null}, "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Data or parameters entering the graph"}]}]}]}, {"type": "tableRow", "content": [{"type": "tableCell", "attrs": {"colspan": 1, "rowspan": 1, "colwidth": null, "align": null}, "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "Operation nodes"}]}]}, {"type": "tableCell", "attrs": {"colspan": 1, "rowspan": 1, "colwidth": null, "align": null}, "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Math operations (e.g., "}, {"type": "inlineMath", "attrs": {"latex": "+"}}, {"type": "text", "text": ", "}, {"type": "inlineMath", "attrs": {"latex": "\\times"}}, {"type": "text", "text": ", activation functions)"}]}]}]}, {"type": "tableRow", "content": [{"type": "tableCell", "attrs": {"colspan": 1, "rowspan": 1, "colwidth": null, "align": null}, "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "Output nodes"}]}]}, {"type": "tableCell", "attrs": {"colspan": 1, "rowspan": 1, "colwidth": null, "align": null}, "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Final results (predictions, loss)"}]}]}]}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "[cs.umd](http://www.cs.umd.edu/class/fall2018/cmsc470/slides/slides_8.pdf)"}]}, {"type": "heading", "attrs": {"level": 3}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Simple example: Computing "}, {"type": "text", "text": "y = wx + b"}]}, {"type": "codeBlock", "attrs": {"language": "text"}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "w ────┐\n      │\n      ● (multiply) ────┐\n      │                │\nx ────┘                │\n                       ● (add) ──── y\n                       │\nb ─────────────────────┘"}]}, {"type": "bulletList", "content": [{"type": "listItem", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Nodes: "}, {"type": "inlineMath", "attrs": {"latex": "w, x, b"}}, {"type": "text", "text": " (inputs), multiply (×), add (+), "}, {"type": "inlineMath", "attrs": {"latex": "y"}}, {"type": "text", "text": " (output)"}]}]}, {"type": "listItem", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Edges: Data flow from inputs through operations to output"}]}]}]}, {"type": "horizontalRule"}, {"type": "heading", "attrs": {"level": 2}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "How Computation Graphs Represent Neural Networks"}]}, {"type": "heading", "attrs": {"level": 3}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Neural networks as computation graphs:"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "A neural network decomposes into "}, {"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "simple operations over matrices and vectors"}, {"type": "text", "text": ":"}]}, {"type": "codeBlock", "attrs": {"language": "text"}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Input X\n  ↓\n[W × X] ── Linear combination ── Z = WX + b\n  ↓\n[b] ────────────────────────────┘\n  ↓\n[g(Z)] ── Activation ── A = g(Z)\n  ↓\nOutput A (to next layer)"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Each layer's computation is represented as a subgraph:"}]}, {"type": "table", "content": [{"type": "tableRow", "content": [{"type": "tableHeader", "attrs": {"colspan": 1, "rowspan": 1, "colwidth": null, "align": null}, "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Layer Operation"}]}]}, {"type": "tableHeader", "attrs": {"colspan": 1, "rowspan": 1, "colwidth": null, "align": null}, "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Graph Representation"}]}]}]}, {"type": "tableRow", "content": [{"type": "tableCell", "attrs": {"colspan": 1, "rowspan": 1, "colwidth": null, "align": null}, "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "Linear combination"}]}]}, {"type": "tableCell", "attrs": {"colspan": 1, "rowspan": 1, "colwidth": null, "align": null}, "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Nodes: "}, {"type": "inlineMath", "attrs": {"latex": "W, X, b"}}, {"type": "text", "text": "; Operations: ×, +"}]}]}]}, {"type": "tableRow", "content": [{"type": "tableCell", "attrs": {"colspan": 1, "rowspan": 1, "colwidth": null, "align": null}, "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "Activation"}]}]}, {"type": "tableCell", "attrs": {"colspan": 1, "rowspan": 1, "colwidth": null, "align": null}, "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Node: "}, {"type": "inlineMath", "attrs": {"latex": "g"}}, {"type": "text", "text": " (activation function); Input: "}, {"type": "inlineMath", "attrs": {"latex": "Z"}}, {"type": "text", "text": "; Output: "}, {"type": "inlineMath", "attrs": {"latex": "A"}}]}]}]}, {"type": "tableRow", "content": [{"type": "tableCell", "attrs": {"colspan": 1, "rowspan": 1, "colwidth": null, "align": null}, "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "Forward pass"}]}]}, {"type": "tableCell", "attrs": {"colspan": 1, "rowspan": 1, "colwidth": null, "align": null}, "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Traverse graph left-to-right"}]}]}]}, {"type": "tableRow", "content": [{"type": "tableCell", "attrs": {"colspan": 1, "rowspan": 1, "colwidth": null, "align": null}, "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "Backward pass"}]}]}, {"type": "tableCell", "attrs": {"colspan": 1, "rowspan": 1, "colwidth": null, "align": null}, "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Traverse graph right-to-left (backpropagation)"}]}]}]}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "[cs.umd](http://www.cs.umd.edu/class/fall2018/cmsc470/slides/slides_8.pdf)"}]}, {"type": "horizontalRule"}, {"type": "heading", "attrs": {"level": 2}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Forward Propagation on a Computation Graph"}]}, {"type": "heading", "attrs": {"level": 3}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Process: Evaluating the graph:"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "Forward propagation"}, {"type": "text", "text": " moves information through the network "}, {"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "from input to output layer by layer"}, {"type": "text", "text": " (left to right in the graph):"}]}, {"type": "codeBlock", "attrs": {"language": "yaml"}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Step-by-step:\n1. Initialize input layer with given data (X)\n2. For each subsequent layer:\n   ├─ Compute weighted sum: z = Wx + b\n   └─ Apply activation: a = f(z)\n3. Repeat until reaching output layer\n4. Output = final prediction"}]}, {"type": "heading", "attrs": {"level": 3}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Algorithm:"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "<table><tbody><tr><td align=\"left\" valign=\"top\">1. Start at input nodes</td><td align=\"left\" valign=\"top\">Load input data X</td></tr><tr><td align=\"left\" valign=\"top\">2. Traverse in topological order</td><td align=\"left\" valign=\"top\">Process nodes in order (inputs → operations → outputs)</td></tr><tr><td align=\"left\" valign=\"top\">3. Evaluate each operation</td><td align=\"left\" valign=\"top\">Compute matrix multiplications, additions, activations</td></tr><tr><td align=\"left\" valign=\"top\">4. Store intermediate results</td><td align=\"left\" valign=\"top\">Save Z, A values for backpropagation</td></tr><tr><td align=\"left\" valign=\"top\">5. Reach output node</td><td align=\"left\" valign=\"top\">Final prediction Y</td></tr></tbody></table>"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "[cs.umd](http://www.cs.umd.edu/class/fall2018/cmsc470/slides/slides_8.pdf)"}]}, {"type": "horizontalRule"}, {"type": "heading", "attrs": {"level": 2}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Visual Example: Computation Graph for a 2-Layer Neural Network"}]}, {"type": "heading", "attrs": {"level": 3}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Network structure:"}]}, {"type": "codeBlock", "attrs": {"language": "text"}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Input X (3 features)\n  ↓\nHidden Layer 1 (2 neurons): Z¹ = W¹X + b¹ → A¹ = ReLU(Z¹)\n  ↓\nHidden Layer 2 (2 neurons): Z² = W²A¹ + b² → A² = ReLU(Z²)\n  ↓\nOutput Layer (1 neuron): Z³ = W³A² + b³ → A³ = sigmoid(Z³)"}]}, {"type": "heading", "attrs": {"level": 3}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Computation graph representation:"}]}, {"type": "codeBlock", "attrs": {"language": "text"}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "                    ┌─ W¹ (weights) ──┐\n                    │                 │\nX ──┬───────────────┼─ × (multiply) ──●─ Z¹ ── ReLU ── A¹ ──┬──→ to Layer 2\n    │               │                 │                    │\n    └─ (identity) ──┼─────────────────┘                    │\n                    │                                      │\n                    └─ b¹ (bias) ── + (add) ──┘            │\n                                                           │\n                                                           │\n                                                       (repeat for Layer 2)\n                                                           │\n                                                           │\nOutput ────────────────────────────────────────────────────┼─ A³\n                                                           │"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "Key insight"}, {"type": "text", "text": ": The graph shows "}, {"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "exactly how data flows"}, {"type": "text", "text": " through the network, making it easy to understand and implement."}]}, {"type": "horizontalRule"}, {"type": "heading", "attrs": {"level": 2}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Why Computation Graphs Are Powerful"}]}, {"type": "heading", "attrs": {"level": 3}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Key benefits:"}]}, {"type": "table", "content": [{"type": "tableRow", "content": [{"type": "tableHeader", "attrs": {"colspan": 1, "rowspan": 1, "colwidth": null, "align": null}, "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Advantage"}]}]}, {"type": "tableHeader", "attrs": {"colspan": 1, "rowspan": 1, "colwidth": null, "align": null}, "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Explanation"}]}]}]}, {"type": "tableRow", "content": [{"type": "tableCell", "attrs": {"colspan": 1, "rowspan": 1, "colwidth": null, "align": null}, "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "Simplifies complex architectures"}]}]}, {"type": "tableCell", "attrs": {"colspan": 1, "rowspan": 1, "colwidth": null, "align": null}, "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Visual representation of data flow aids understanding"}]}]}]}, {"type": "tableRow", "content": [{"type": "tableCell", "attrs": {"colspan": 1, "rowspan": 1, "colwidth": null, "align": null}, "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "Enables efficient backpropagation"}]}]}, {"type": "tableCell", "attrs": {"colspan": 1, "rowspan": 1, "colwidth": null, "align": null}, "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Facilitates automatic gradient computation by traversing graph backward"}]}]}]}, {"type": "tableRow", "content": [{"type": "tableCell", "attrs": {"colspan": 1, "rowspan": 1, "colwidth": null, "align": null}, "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "Foundation for neural network libraries"}]}]}, {"type": "tableCell", "attrs": {"colspan": 1, "rowspan": 1, "colwidth": null, "align": null}, "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "TensorFlow, PyTorch, MXNet all built on computation graphs"}]}]}]}, {"type": "tableRow", "content": [{"type": "tableCell", "attrs": {"colspan": 1, "rowspan": 1, "colwidth": null, "align": null}, "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "Automatic differentiation"}]}]}, {"type": "tableCell", "attrs": {"colspan": 1, "rowspan": 1, "colwidth": null, "align": null}, "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "PyTorch automatically builds graph during forward pass, computes gradients during backward pass"}]}]}]}, {"type": "tableRow", "content": [{"type": "tableCell", "attrs": {"colspan": 1, "rowspan": 1, "colwidth": null, "align": null}, "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "Easy to implement"}]}]}, {"type": "tableCell", "attrs": {"colspan": 1, "rowspan": 1, "colwidth": null, "align": null}, "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Prediction = forward pass through graph; Training = backward pass"}]}]}]}, {"type": "tableRow", "content": [{"type": "tableCell", "attrs": {"colspan": 1, "rowspan": 1, "colwidth": null, "align": null}, "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "Modular design"}]}]}, {"type": "tableCell", "attrs": {"colspan": 1, "rowspan": 1, "colwidth": null, "align": null}, "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Can reuse subgraphs (e.g., attention layers, CNN blocks)"}]}]}]}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "[pub.towardsai](https://pub.towardsai.net/understanding-computational-graphs-and-backpropagation-a-deep-dive-into-deep-learning-525ecf07dda2)"}]}, {"type": "horizontalRule"}, {"type": "heading", "attrs": {"level": 2}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Forward vs Backward Pass on Computation Graphs"}]}, {"type": "heading", "attrs": {"level": 3}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Two passes through the same graph:"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "<table><thead><tr><th align=\"left\" valign=\"top\">Pass</th><th align=\"left\" valign=\"top\">Direction</th><th align=\"left\" valign=\"top\">Purpose</th><th align=\"left\" valign=\"top\">What it computes</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td align=\"left\" valign=\"top\">"}, {"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "Forward Propagation"}, {"type": "text", "text": "</td><td align=\"left\" valign=\"top\">Left → Right<br>(input → output)</td><td align=\"left\" valign=\"top\">Make predictions</td><td align=\"left\" valign=\"top\">Network output given input<br>"}, {"type": "inlineMath", "attrs": {"latex": "Y = f(X)"}}, {"type": "text", "text": "</td></tr><tr><td align=\"left\" valign=\"top\">"}, {"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "Backward Propagation"}, {"type": "text", "text": "<br>(Backpropagation)</td><td align=\"left\" valign=\"top\">Right → Left<br>(output → input)</td><td align=\"left\" valign=\"top\">Train the model</td><td align=\"left\" valign=\"top\">Gradients of loss w.r.t. weights<br>"}, {"type": "inlineMath", "attrs": {"latex": "\\frac{\\partial \\text{Loss}}{\\partial W}"}}, {"type": "text", "text": "</td></tr></tbody></table>"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "[cs.umd](http://www.cs.umd.edu/class/fall2018/cmsc470/slides/slides_8.pdf)"}]}, {"type": "heading", "attrs": {"level": 3}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "How backpropagation uses the graph:"}]}, {"type": "codeBlock", "attrs": {"language": "text"}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Forward pass (store intermediate values):\nX → Z¹ → A¹ → Z² → A² → Z³ → A³ → Loss\n\nBackward pass (compute gradients):\nLoss ← ∂Loss/∂A³ ← ∂Loss/∂Z³ ← ∂Loss/∂A² ← ... ← ∂Loss/∂X"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "PyTorch automatically builds the computational graph during forward pass and computes all gradients during backward pass."}]}, {"type": "horizontalRule"}, {"type": "heading", "attrs": {"level": 2}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Computation Graph in Modern Deep Learning Libraries"}]}, {"type": "heading", "attrs": {"level": 3}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "TensorFlow (static graph):"}]}, {"type": "codeBlock", "attrs": {"language": "python"}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "import tensorflow as tf\n\n# Define graph structure\nx = tf.placeholder(tf.float32, [None, 3])\nW = tf.Variable(tf.random_normal([3, 2]))\nb = tf.Variable(tf.zeros( [cs.umd](http://www.cs.umd.edu/class/fall2018/cmsc470/slides/slides_8.pdf)))\nZ = tf.matmul(x, W) + b\nA = tf.nn.relu(Z)\n\n# Forward pass: evaluate graph\noutput = model.predict(input_data)"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Graph is defined first, then executed."}]}, {"type": "horizontalRule"}, {"type": "heading", "attrs": {"level": 3}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "PyTorch (dynamic graph):"}]}, {"type": "codeBlock", "attrs": {"language": "python"}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "import torch\n\n# Define model\nclass Net(nn.Module):\n    def forward(self, x):\n        Z = torch.matmul(x, W) + b\n        A = torch.relu(Z)\n        return A\n\n# Forward pass: automatically builds graph\nmodel = Net()\noutput = model(input_data)  # Graph built here\n\n# Backward pass: automatically computes gradients\nloss = compute_loss(output, target)\nloss.backward()  # Backpropagation through graph"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Graph is built dynamically during forward pass."}]}, {"type": "horizontalRule"}, {"type": "heading", "attrs": {"level": 2}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Trade-offs: Static vs Dynamic Computation Graphs"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "The two dominant paradigms for constructing computation graphs — static (define-then-run) and dynamic (define-by-run) — each have distinct trade-offs that affect debugging, performance, and deployment."}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Static graphs (TensorFlow 1.x, JAX with jit) are defined once before any data flows through them. The framework can perform global optimisations — operator fusion, memory planning, constant folding — because it sees the full graph before execution. This yields faster inference on fixed-architecture models. The downside is inflexibility: variable-length sequences, branching control flow, and dynamic architectures are awkward to express."}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Dynamic graphs (PyTorch eager mode) are built fresh each time the forward pass runs. This makes debugging natural — you can set breakpoints, print tensors, and inspect graph structure at any point — and allows fully dynamic architectures where the graph shape depends on input values. The trade-off is that each new input rebuilds the graph, preventing certain global optimisations."}]}, {"type": "table", "content": [{"type": "tableRow", "content": [{"type": "tableHeader", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Property"}]}]}, {"type": "tableHeader", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Static graph"}]}]}, {"type": "tableHeader", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Dynamic graph"}]}]}]}, {"type": "tableRow", "content": [{"type": "tableCell", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Debugging"}]}]}, {"type": "tableCell", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Hard — graph compiled before execution"}]}]}, {"type": "tableCell", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Easy — inspect tensors in Python debugger"}]}]}]}, {"type": "tableRow", "content": [{"type": "tableCell", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Inference speed"}]}]}, {"type": "tableCell", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Faster — global optimisations available"}]}]}, {"type": "tableCell", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Slightly slower by default; compilable with torch.compile"}]}]}]}, {"type": "tableRow", "content": [{"type": "tableCell", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Dynamic architectures"}]}]}, {"type": "tableCell", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Awkward — requires explicit control flow ops"}]}]}, {"type": "tableCell", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Natural — use Python if/while directly"}]}]}]}, {"type": "tableRow", "content": [{"type": "tableCell", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Deployment"}]}]}, {"type": "tableCell", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Easy — graph is serialisable"}]}]}, {"type": "tableCell", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Requires tracing or compilation for production"}]}]}]}]}, {"type": "heading", "attrs": {"level": 2}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "When to Think in Computation Graphs"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Computation graphs are not just an implementation detail — they are a thinking tool. When designing a new neural architecture, drawing the computation graph first (even on paper) reveals how information flows, where gradients can vanish or explode, and which operations can be parallelised. If a path through the graph is very long, you have identified a potential vanishing gradient problem before writing a line of code."}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Graphs are also the natural representation for diagnosing training failures. If loss is not decreasing, the computation graph tells you where to look: which operation is saturating activations, whether gradients reach early layers, and whether skip connections are providing the shortcut paths needed for gradient flow."}]}, {"type": "bulletList", "content": [{"type": "listItem", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "Use computation graph thinking when:"}, {"type": "text", "text": " designing novel architectures, debugging gradient flow, optimising for inference speed, or explaining model behaviour to collaborators."}]}]}, {"type": "listItem", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "Skip the graph abstraction when:"}, {"type": "text", "text": " prototyping simple feedforward networks, doing quick exploratory data analysis, or using high-level APIs (Keras Sequential) that manage the graph automatically."}]}]}]}, {"type": "heading", "attrs": {"level": 2}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Common Mistakes"}]}, {"type": "bulletList", "content": [{"type": "listItem", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "Calling backward() on the wrong tensor."}, {"type": "text", "text": " loss.backward() must be called on a scalar. Calling it on a non-scalar tensor raises an error or requires a gradient argument. Always reduce to a scalar before calling backward."}]}]}, {"type": "listItem", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "Forgetting to zero gradients."}, {"type": "text", "text": " PyTorch accumulates gradients by default. Without optimizer.zero_grad() before each backward pass, gradients from previous iterations add to the current ones, corrupting weight updates."}]}]}, {"type": "listItem", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "Detaching tensors when gradients are needed."}, {"type": "text", "text": " Calling .detach() or .numpy() on a tensor breaks the computation graph. The gradient cannot flow through a detached edge, silently preventing learning in affected parameters."}]}]}, {"type": "listItem", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "In-place operations on tracked tensors."}, {"type": "text", "text": " In-place ops (x += y instead of x = x + y) modify the tensor's storage without creating a new graph node, which can cause incorrect or undefined gradients."}]}]}, {"type": "listItem", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "Graph memory leaks in training loops."}, {"type": "text", "text": " Storing loss.item() stores only the scalar. Storing loss itself stores the entire computation graph, causing memory to grow unboundedly over training iterations."}]}]}]}, {"type": "codeBlock", "attrs": {"language": "python"}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "import torch\nimport torch.nn as nn\n\n# Common mistakes and their fixes\nmodel = nn.Linear(10, 1)\noptimizer = torch.optim.SGD(model.parameters(), lr=0.01)\nx = torch.randn(32, 10)\ny = torch.randn(32, 1)\n\n# WRONG: no zero_grad -> gradient accumulation across iterations\nfor _ in range(3):\n    loss = nn.functional.mse_loss(model(x), y)\n    loss.backward()          # gradients ACCUMULATE\n    optimizer.step()\n\n# CORRECT\nfor _ in range(3):\n    optimizer.zero_grad()    # clear accumulated gradients first\n    loss = nn.functional.mse_loss(model(x), y)\n    loss.backward()\n    optimizer.step()\n\n# WRONG: storing the full loss tensor causes memory leak\nlosses = []\nfor _ in range(100):\n    loss = nn.functional.mse_loss(model(x), y)\n    losses.append(loss)      # stores graph for every iteration\n\n# CORRECT: detach the scalar\nlosses = []\nfor _ in range(100):\n    optimizer.zero_grad()\n    loss = nn.functional.mse_loss(model(x), y)\n    loss.backward()\n    optimizer.step()\n    losses.append(loss.item())  # .item() detaches and returns Python float\n"}]}, {"type": "heading", "attrs": {"level": 2}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Best Practices"}]}, {"type": "bulletList", "content": [{"type": "listItem", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "Use torch.no_grad() during inference."}, {"type": "text", "text": " This disables gradient tracking, reducing memory usage and speeding up forward passes by ~30-50% when no backward pass is needed."}]}]}, {"type": "listItem", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "Use torch.compile() for production."}, {"type": "text", "text": " PyTorch 2.x's compile step converts the dynamic graph to an optimised static representation, closing most of the performance gap with TensorFlow's static graphs."}]}]}, {"type": "listItem", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "Profile gradient flow in deep models."}, {"type": "text", "text": " Use gradient histograms in TensorBoard to detect vanishing or exploding gradients early in training rather than diagnosing them after a failed run."}]}]}, {"type": "listItem", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "Draw the graph before coding it."}, {"type": "text", "text": " For novel architectures, sketch nodes and edges on paper first. Reviewing the graph reveals skip-connection opportunities and shows which paths may suffer from vanishing gradients."}]}]}, {"type": "listItem", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "Verify gradients on small models."}, {"type": "text", "text": " Use torch.autograd.gradcheck on custom layers to confirm that analytical gradients match numerical approximations before scaling up."}]}]}]}, {"type": "heading", "attrs": {"level": 2}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Performance and Scalability"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "The computational complexity of a forward pass through a computation graph is determined by the most expensive operations in the graph — typically matrix multiplications. For a linear layer mapping n inputs to m outputs with batch size b, the cost is O(b * n * m) multiply-accumulate operations. A deep network with L layers stacks these, giving total cost O(b * sum_l(n_l * m_l))."}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Memory consumption is dominated by the intermediate activations that must be stored for the backward pass. For a model with L layers and batch size b, the activation memory grows as O(b * L * d) where d is the average layer width. Gradient checkpointing (recomputing activations during the backward pass instead of storing them) reduces memory to O(sqrt(L)) at the cost of an extra forward pass."}]}, {"type": "codeBlock", "attrs": {"language": "python"}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "import torch\nimport torch.nn as nn\nfrom torch.utils.checkpoint import checkpoint_sequential\n\n# Gradient checkpointing: trade compute for memory\n# Useful for very deep models that do not fit in GPU memory\n\nclass DeepModel(nn.Module):\n    def __init__(self, depth: int = 50):\n        super().__init__()\n        self.layers = nn.Sequential(*[\n            nn.Sequential(nn.Linear(256, 256), nn.ReLU())\n            for _ in range(depth)\n        ])\n\n    def forward(self, x, use_checkpointing: bool = False):\n        if use_checkpointing:\n            # Recomputes activations during backward pass instead of storing them\n            # Memory: O(sqrt(L)) instead of O(L)\n            return checkpoint_sequential(self.layers, segments=5, input=x)\n        return self.layers(x)\n\n# Inference: disable gradient tracking for 30-50% speedup\nmodel = nn.Linear(512, 10)\nmodel.eval()\nx = torch.randn(64, 512)\n\nwith torch.no_grad():\n    output = model(x)  # no graph built; 2x less memory than training mode\n\n# Compile for production (PyTorch 2.x)\ncompiled_model = torch.compile(model, mode=\"reduce-overhead\")\nwith torch.no_grad():\n    output = compiled_model(x)  # typically 10-30% faster after warmup\n"}]}, {"type": "heading", "attrs": {"level": 2}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Tooling and Ecosystem"}]}, {"type": "table", "content": [{"type": "tableRow", "content": [{"type": "tableHeader", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Tool"}]}]}, {"type": "tableHeader", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Graph type"}]}]}, {"type": "tableHeader", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Strengths"}]}]}]}, {"type": "tableRow", "content": [{"type": "tableCell", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "PyTorch (eager)"}]}]}, {"type": "tableCell", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Dynamic"}]}]}, {"type": "tableCell", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Debugging, research, dynamic architectures (RNNs, graph nets)"}]}]}]}, {"type": "tableRow", "content": [{"type": "tableCell", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "PyTorch + torch.compile"}]}]}, {"type": "tableCell", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Dynamic -> Static"}]}]}, {"type": "tableCell", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Production speed with dynamic-graph developer experience"}]}]}]}, {"type": "tableRow", "content": [{"type": "tableCell", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "JAX + jit"}]}]}, {"type": "tableCell", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Functional static"}]}]}, {"type": "tableCell", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Maximum XLA optimisation; hardware-agnostic accelerator support"}]}]}]}, {"type": "tableRow", "content": [{"type": "tableCell", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "TensorFlow 2 / Keras"}]}]}, {"type": "tableCell", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Eager + optional static"}]}]}, {"type": "tableCell", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Production deployment (TF Serving, TFLite, SavedModel)"}]}]}]}, {"type": "tableRow", "content": [{"type": "tableCell", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "torchviz"}]}]}, {"type": "tableCell", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Visualisation"}]}]}, {"type": "tableCell", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Renders PyTorch autograd graphs as graphviz diagrams for inspection"}]}]}]}]}, {"type": "heading", "attrs": {"level": 2}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Security and Reliability"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Computation graph reliability is primarily a numerical stability concern. Deep graphs with many sequential operations can accumulate floating-point errors, causing training instability. The most common failure mode is gradient explosion in very deep recurrent networks, where gradients multiply through hundreds of time steps and can reach values that overflow float16."}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Mitigation strategies include gradient clipping (capping the L2 norm of the gradient vector before the update step), mixed-precision training with loss scaling (scale the loss up before backward, scale gradients back down after), and architectural choices like residual connections that provide skip paths with gradient magnitude near 1."}]}, {"type": "codeBlock", "attrs": {"language": "python"}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "import torch\nimport torch.nn as nn\n\n# Gradient clipping: prevents exploding gradients\nmodel = nn.LSTM(256, 512, num_layers=4, batch_first=True)\noptimizer = torch.optim.Adam(model.parameters(), lr=1e-3)\n\nx = torch.randn(16, 100, 256)   # batch=16, seq_len=100, features=256\ntarget = torch.randn(16, 100, 512)\n\noptimizer.zero_grad()\noutput, _ = model(x)\nloss = nn.functional.mse_loss(output, target)\nloss.backward()\n\n# Clip gradients to max L2 norm of 1.0 before the update\ntorch.nn.utils.clip_grad_norm_(model.parameters(), max_norm=1.0)\noptimizer.step()\n\n# Check for NaN/Inf in gradients (useful during debugging)\nfor name, param in model.named_parameters():\n    if param.grad is not None:\n        if not torch.isfinite(param.grad).all():\n            print(f\"WARNING: non-finite gradient in {name}\")\n"}]}, {"type": "heading", "attrs": {"level": 2}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Key Takeaways"}]}, {"type": "bulletList", "content": [{"type": "listItem", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "Computation graph"}, {"type": "text", "text": ": Visual representation of data flow in neural networks with nodes (variables/operations) and edges (data flow)"}]}]}, {"type": "listItem", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "Nodes"}, {"type": "text", "text": ": Represent inputs, weights, biases, activations, or mathematical operations (×, +, activation functions)"}]}]}, {"type": "listItem", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "Edges"}, {"type": "text", "text": ": Directional flow of data (tensors) between nodes"}]}]}, {"type": "listItem", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "Forward propagation"}, {"type": "text", "text": ": Traverse graph "}, {"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "left to right"}, {"type": "text", "text": " (input → output), computing predictions"}]}]}, {"type": "listItem", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "Backpropagation"}, {"type": "text", "text": ": Traverse graph "}, {"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "right to left"}, {"type": "text", "text": " (output → input), computing gradients"}]}]}, {"type": "listItem", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "Topological order"}, {"type": "text", "text": ": Process nodes in order (inputs → operations → outputs) for forward pass"}]}]}, {"type": "listItem", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "Decomposes computation"}, {"type": "text", "text": ": Neural networks = simple operations over matrices and vectors"}]}]}, {"type": "listItem", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "Foundation for libraries"}, {"type": "text", "text": ": TensorFlow, PyTorch, MXNet all built on computation graphs"}]}]}, {"type": "listItem", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "Automatic differentiation"}, {"type": "text", "text": ": PyTorch automatically builds graph during forward pass, computes gradients during backward pass"}]}]}, {"type": "listItem", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "Simplifies complex architectures"}, {"type": "text", "text": ": Visual representation aids understanding and implementation"}]}]}, {"type": "listItem", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "Enables efficient training"}, {"type": "text", "text": ": Backpropagation algorithm computes derivatives by traversing graph"}]}]}, {"type": "listItem", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "Modern deep learning"}, {"type": "text", "text": ": Forms basis for all neural network implementations"}]}]}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Computation graphs are the fundamental abstraction that makes modern deep learning possible—they provide the structure for automatic differentiation, efficient computation, and intuitive understanding of how neural networks process data during forward propagation and learn during backpropagation."}]}]}}